@NODE INTRO "Introduction"

Introduction:

   Dave's Space Empire (DSE) is a "door" game for play online on Amiga
   bulletin board systems (BBS's).  The game is a multi-player game
   where participants compete to build the largest "space empire".  The
   game involves military strategy, cooperation with other players, and
   you musn't forget to keep the people in your own empire happy.  By
   purchasing and/or conquering various types of planets, players gain
   population, the resources of the particular planet, and points.
   When a player reaches 100,000 points, they become "Space Lord".  They
   do not automatically win, however, they must retain their Space Lord
   status for one week (seven days).

   Dave's Space Empire is a "DOS" door game as to make it compatible
   with as many BBS packages as possible.  It may also be run from a CLI
   window.  It supports ANSI colors and IBM graphics, each of which can
   be turned on/off by each individual user.  Also, all menus are ASCII
   text files that may be changed with any text editor.  Also, EVERY
   message displayed by the game is in one large text file so that
   SysOps can customize the game and colors of the text as much as
   possible.

   To determine exactly which version you have, go into a Shell and type
   "Version DSE" at the prompt.  Also, the DSEcfg and DSE-Msgs.txt files
   have version strings in them.  Make sure all three files have the same
   version number before using them together.  DSE-Msgs.txt is in the
   Text directory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DISTR "Distribution"

Distribution:

   This program is freeware, however, if you distribute it, you MUST
   distribute ALL files together.  A listing of the files is as follows:

      DSE                 - Main executable program.
      DSEcfg              - Sets up a few variables and resets the game.
                            Mouse-driven, WB 2.04 and above, only.
      DSEcfg.info         - Icon file for DSEcfg program.
      DSEcfg-CLI          - CLI-based DSEcfg.  Also is Workbench 1.3 compatible.
      DSEdoc.guide        - This file in AmigaGuide format.
      DSEdoc.guide.info   - Icon file for AmigaGuide documentation.
      powerpacker.library - Library for reading compressed Text/ files.
      Text/               - Directory of text files.
          |
          Agricultural.txt   - Info file on Agricultural planets.
          Bank.mnu           - Bank menu file.
          Covert.mnu         - Covert Operations menu file.
          Defense.txt        - Info file on Defense planets.
          Documentation.txt  - Full DSE documentation file.
          DSE-Msgs.txt       - DSE text messages file.
          GovActions.mnu     - Government Actions menu file.
          Intro.txt          - Introduction info file.
          Main.mnu           - Main menu file (before game).
          Mining.txt         - Info file on Ore Mining planets.
          NewPlayer.txt      - New Player display file.
          Radio.mnu          - Radio Network menu file.
          Research.txt       - Info file on Research planets.
          Special1.mnu       - Special Missions menu file.
          Special2.mnu       - Special Missions menu file.
          Special3.mnu       - Special Missions menu file.
          Special4.mnu       - Special Missions menu file.
          TBank.mnu          - Team Bank menu file.
          TeamLeader.mnu     - Team menu file for a team leader.
          TeamMember.mnu     - Team menu file for normal members.
          TeamNone.mnu       - Team menu file for a non-member.
          Training.txt       - Info file on Training planets.


@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTL "Installation"

Installation:

NOTE: Pre-2.0 DSE users, this 2.0 version is *NOT* compatible with older
      versions.  Please delete your old version and start over from
      scratch.  My apologies, but it has undergone radical changes.


To install DSE follow these simple steps:


1) Copy the included powerpacker.library to your LIBS: directory.  This
   will allow you to use PowerPacker or other compression utility that uses
   the powerpacker.library to compress any files in the Text/ directory.


2) Create a directory somewhere on your hard-drive and put all of the
   included files in that directory.  Make sure that subdirectories are
   maintained.  For example, if you copy DSE to the directory DH0:DSE, then
   there would have to be a DH0:DSE/Text directory as well, with all of the
   text files under that directory.  Also, create a "Messages" (no quotes)
   directory UNDER the DSE directory.  You will not copy any files here.

   If you were using DH0:DSE for your path, your directory structure would
   look like so:

                DH0:
                    DSE/
                        Text/
                        Messages/


   NOTE: If your BBS program requires doors to be in a certain directory,
   then you should follow those guidlines.


3) Run the DSEcfg program from Workbench by double-clicking on its icon, or
   from the Shell.  This program will only run under Workbench 2.04 or
   above.  If you are still running 1.3, then you can use the DSEcfg-CLI
   program which has been included.  It will only run from a shell.

   When the program is run, do not reset the game, as there is no need to do
   this.  Set the other options as you see fit.  Simply click on Save to
   use the default values.


4) Now select your BBS program here.  Select "General" if you do not see
   your BBS software listed here.  You may also want to read "General" if
   you want a more in depth description of how DSE can be run.

       @{" General    " link GENRL}
       @{" CNet AMIGA " link CNET}
       @{" DLG-Pro    " link DLGPR}
       @{" Excelsior! " link EXCEL}
       @{" Starnet    " link STARN}
       @{" TransAmiga " link TRANS}
       @{" AXsh       " link AXSH}
       @{" NiKom      " link NIKOM}

@ENDNODE

@NODE GENRL "General Installation"

   You need to find out how to run a "DOS" or "CLI" door from your BBS
   program.  Refer to your documentation on how to do this.  Often times
   there is a hack or third-party program for doing this that may not be
   documented, so find someone who is a "guru" with your particular BBS
   software and ask him/her.

   Once you have discovered how to launch a DOS door from your BBS
   software, then you need to setup your BBS to call the DSE executable
   like so:

   Path:To/DSE/Files/DSE <opt> <userid>

   Obviously, the "Path:To/DSE/Files/" is where you stick the path where you
   copied the DSE files and DSE is the executable filename.

   Next, the <opt> is how you want DSE to do the I/O.  DSE _requires_ "RAW"
   mode for operation, but there are two ways to accomplish this.  The
   first way is by specifying "-d" (no quotes) as the <opt>.  This will
   have DSE force RAW mode itself.  Some BBS programs don't like this, but
   do have the option of opening the I/O with RAW mode BEFORE running the
   executable.  If your BBS is one of these, then tell your BBS to run the
   door with RAW mode "ON" and use "-n" for the <opt>.

   Last, you need to supply some sort of identification unique to the user
   currently online.  This could be their name or ID number (possibly phone
   number, but my system has different callers from one family that all
   have the same phone number, of course, so be careful here).  To do this,
   many BBS programs have special codes you supply.  For example, %3 is a
   user's name on CNet.  Remember that names may have spaces in them, so
   you should put quotes around them.

   Here's an example of what you might put into the command line:

   DH0:DSE/DSE -d "%NAME"

   Note that this will run the DSE executable if it is in the DH0:DSE
   directory with RAW mode forced and assumes that %NAME is the code to
   insert the user online's real name into the command line for the
   particular BBS program.  Note that there are quotes around it.  This is
   HIGHLY recommended, as names usually have spaces in them.

	There are two more options you can add afer the user id.  One is the
   node id.  See the rest of main installation for a description of this.
   The other option is the FIFO keyword.  If your BBS uses the FIFO: device
   to run DOS doors, you should use this keyword at the end of your command
   line.

   If you successfully install DSE for a BBS program that is not documented
   in this file, then please consider writing a doc file for your BBS and
   @{"sending it to me." link AUTHR}

   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE CNET "CNet AMIGA Installation"

                          CNet v2.63 INSTALLATION
             Written by Capt. Pez, Sysop of Needful Things BBS
                    Needful Things BBS: 1-206-475-0884


1) DSE _MUST_ be run as a "DOS" door from CNet. You would add it like this:

   =========================================================================

   DOS Filename: Pfiles:DSE/DSE        (The path and name of the file)
   Description : Dave's Space Empire   (What you are going to call it)
   Arguments   : -n "%1"               (Options AND user ID - See Below)

   =========================================================================
   
   DSE requires that RAW console mode be set to YES.  The -n option tells
   DSE that you will be running the executable under RAW mode from CNet. 
   This is VERY important!  Make sure RAW mode is set to 'yes' and that
   you have the -n option set in the arguments.  
   
   Also make sure you have CNet's "Echo Input" switch set to NO.
   
   Note that this will run the DSE executable if it is in the PFILES:DSE
   directory with RAW mode forced and assumes that %1 is the code to insert 
   the user online's real name into the command line for CNet.  Note that 
   there are quotes around it.  This is REQUIRED, as names usually have 
   spaces in them.

   That's all you need to do for the arguments!  Easy eh?


2) If you are having ANY trouble with installing this on your BBS, feel free
   to contact me (Capt. Pez) on Needful Things BBS (206) 475-0884 OR leave
   me mail on Future World.  I call Future World at least once a month, so
   if you want a quick reply, your best bet is to contact me on my BBS.


   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE DLGPR "DLG-Pro Installation"

                           DLG Pro INSTALLATION
                    DLG/DSE Beta Tester: John Freeland
        Freeland's Mainframe BBS: 1-206-438-2273 or 1-206-438-6013


Unfortunately, I don't have any specific docs for DLG, but, from what I'm
told, you want to run it like so:

                            DSE -n %<var>

Replace %<var> with a DLG variable for something like the user's name or
id number.  Also make sure you run the door with RAW mode _ON_.

That should do it!  If you have any problems, contact the BBS above, or
John Freeland's e-mail address is: scotty@freemf.eskimo.com.

                                            -David Prothero

   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE EXCEL "Excelsior! Installation"

                          Excelsior! INSTALLATION
                  Excelsior/DSE Beta Tester: Scott Wiard
                   Digital Dreams II BBS: 1-206-736-2480

NOTE: This install was performed under Excelsior! version 0.996.  Future
      versions will most likely be the same, or very similar.

1) Login as SysOp and go into the <D>oors area.  If you wish, go into the
   subdirectory you want to put DSE in.

2) Type 'A' to add a new door (this is the default command key, use the
   appropriate key if you've changed it).

3) It will then ask you the disk directory to search.  Enter the directory
   you installed DSE in here.  Then, enter "DSE" (no quotes) for the pattern.

4) Say 'Y' to the DSE file and 'N' to the other files.

5) Enter the description and access levels you want.

6) Now enter 'D' for DOS door and then "-d %16" (no quotes) for the DOS
   Arguments.  (%16 is the code for the user ID number.)

   NOTE: Some versions of Excelsior! have a bug in the DOS door interface.
   If the game appears double-spaced to REMOTE callers (not local), then
   use "-e %16" instead for the arguments.  As of right now (0.996) this
   bug has not been fixed.

7) Don't worry about the stack size, leave the priority at zero, and the
   IPL variable at zero.

8) Set the days to keep however you want (0 to keep forever) and set the
   "Only one user at a time" to 'N' (the game keeps it's own locks).

   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE STARN "Starnet BBS Installation"

                         STARNET BBS INSTALLATION
            Written by Larry Cloud, Sysop of Cloud's Corner BBS
                    Cloud's Corner BBS: 1-206-377-4290


NOTE: This will ONLY work with Amigados 2.0 or higher due to the DOSDRIVER
      program for Starnet.

1) ADD the following lines to your LOGON_x.PRX file(s).  If you don't HAVE a
   LOGON_x.PRX file, call Cloud's Corner and grab his "L-ON-OFF.LHA" archive
   (make sure you change the _1 to _0 for line 0, _2 for line 2, etc):

   ---> Cut Here <---

   quote = d2c(34)
   OPEN('file','dosdrivers:dse_1','W')
   WRITELN('file','cd doors:dse')
   WRITELN('file','changetaskpri 2')
   WRITELN('file','dse -d '||quote||username||quote)
   WRITELN('file','changetaskpri 0')
   WRITELN('file','endcli')
   CLOSE('file')
   address command "protect dosdrivers:dse_1 +S"

   ---> Cut Here <---

2) In your DOORS:DOSDRIVERS directory, copy a copy of dosdrivers and rename
   it to DSE.

3) Create the following script in your DOORS:DOSDRIVERS directory and name
   it "DSE.SCRIPT":

   ---> Cut Here <---

   .KEY NODE/A
   .BRA {
   .KET }
   cd dosdrivers:
   c:copy dse_{NODE} dse.sch
   wait 1
   run > NIL: dse {NODE}
   endcli

   ---> Cut Here <---

4) Next, make a menu entry that launches it:

   Option '7':
   Function Rundoor dosdrivers:dse.script
   end

   You can of course assign a different key to it.


   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE TRANS "TransAmiga BBS Installation"

                        TransAmiga BBS INSTALLATION
          Written by David Prothero, Sysop of Digital Dreams III
                    Digital Dreams III: 1-206-650-2582


1) Install DSE in a directory called DSE under your BBS:Extras/ directory.

2) Take the following, copy it to a file named DSE.trans and put it in your
   BBS:Rexx/ directory:

---> Cut Here <---

/* Runs DSE */

options results

systeminfo 8 ; bbsline=result
userinfo a ; name = result
id=time(s)

call open(fp,'t:dserun.'id,'W')
call writeln(fp,'Failat 99999')
call writeln(fp,'cd BBS:Extras/DSE')
call writeln(fp,'DSE -d "'name'" FIFO')
call writeln(fp,'endcli >nil:')
call close(fp)

address command 'NewShell FIFO:trshell'id'/rwkecs from t:dserun.'id
address command 'BBS:Bin/TrShell -n'bbsline' -ftrshell'id
address command 'delete t:dserun.'id

exit

---> Cut Here <---

3) Next, add the DSE.trans to your BBS:Configs/Extras.Rx file.  Refer to
   the TransAmiga documentation on how to do this.


   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AXsh "AXsh Installation"

                          AXsh v1.3 INSTALLATION
                Written by Jani Poijärvi, Sysop of Brahman
                         Brahman: +358-90-498-797

Installing DSE with AXsh is quite simple.  If you want DSE to be accessible
from the shell, rename DSE to DSE.EXE, and add the following lines
to these files:

etc/rc:			<path>/DSE.EXE
etc/globallogin:	alias DSE "DSE.EXE -d $user"

Then typing "DSE" in the shell will load the door.  Unfortunately, this is
susceptible to cheating by sneaky users, so it's better to install DSE
only under a menu system like Matrix (this will not work in Topic).  Just
add the following menu entry:

	d
	<path>/DSE -d $user
	---

If you want to use DSE in local mode in 4 colors instead of 1 or 16, or you
want to give your users the option of doing so, create the following little
script and name it "Launch_DSE":

	For AXshell:			For Matrix:				

	If $terminal == "vt100"		If $terminal EQ "vt100"
		DSE -s $user			<path>/DSE -s $user
	Else				Else
		DSE -d $user			<path>/DSE -d $user
	EndIf				EndIf

For AXshell, place this script in a public directory and change the
alias to "execute axsh:<directory>/Launch_DSE".  For Matrix, place the
script in the DSE directory and change the menu entry to:

	d
	C:Execute <path>/Launch_DSE
	---

This way, if $terminal is "vt100", DSE will load up in 4-color mode,
otherwise it'll use all 16 colors.

That's all there is to it!  Raw mode is internally set by DSE, so you
don't have to set the "r" flags.  If you have trouble setting up DSE,
mail me at root@brahman.nullnet.fi, or call Brahman.


   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE NIKOM "NiKom Installation"

                            NiKom INSTALLATION
                        Written by Niklas Lindholm
                            BBS: +46-8-7925206

1. Make sure you have installed Fifo by Matt Dillon correctly in your system.
   (Fifo comes with the demo version on the Extras disk)

2. Find a ARexx-program number between 1000 and 1999 (I.e.
   NiKom:Rexx/ExtKom1000.nik to ExtKom1999.nik).

3. Make an ARexx-program (eg ExtKom1040.nik) that may look like this:

/* Start Dave's Space Empire */

parse arg nod pers .

options results

'runfifo Yourpath/DSE -d' pers 'FIFO'   /* Note the FIFO option. */

4. Insert an entry in NiKom:DatoCfg/Kommandon.cfg that may look like this:

N=SPACE EMPIRE
S=20
O=2
#=1040

5. Reread the config-files with the command "ReadConfig" and the command
   "Space Empire" is ready to be used.


   @{"Continue at step 5 of main installation." link STEP5}

@ENDNODE

@NODE STEP5 "Installation"

5) To run from a Shell, use -s for the <opt>, and manually enter the
   <userid>.  Example:

      1.dh0:DSE> DSE -s "David Prothero"

   All this does is force RAW mode (which needs to be done from a shell)
   and also remaps ANSI colors so that the text is readable from a normal
   four color Workbench.  If you wish, you could run with a -d <opt> and
   you would get 8 color ANSI, with the intense versions just being in bold.


6) @{"Repeat step 3)" link INSTL} using a DIFFERENT path (with copies of all
   the files also in that path) if you want to run multiple games at one
   time.  Also, you MUST specifiy a different node id for each different
   copy of DSE you want to run.  For example, if your command line were:
   DH0:DSE/DSE -d "%NAME"  -- then you would need to make it:
   DH0:DSE/DSE -d "%NAME" 1 -- where the 1 is an id for each game.  For
   each different game you run, you MUST use a different node id.


7) To reset the game, all you need to do is run the DSEcfg program and
   click on the Reset Game gadget.  If you are using DSEcfg-CLI, then run
   it from a Shell and say "Yes" to the first question where it asks if you
   want to reset the current game.  You usually won't have to do this, as the
   game automatically resets after someone wins.


8) You may customize any of the text files in the Text directory.  Please
   note that these do not use ANSI codes, but special codes that are
   interpretted by DSE.  This way you do NOT need two files, one for ANSI
   and one for non-ANSI.  Also, any IBM style graphics are automatically
   interpretted to dashes, etc. if the user turns off IBM graphics, so feel
   free to use these as well.

   @{"Info on text codes." link CODES}

   IMPORTANT: When editing the DSE-Msgs.txt file, DO NOT INSERT OR DELETE
              ANY LINES!!!  You will basically screw up the game BIG TIME!
              Lines may be as long as your text editor will allow you to
              type, but the bigger your DSE-Msgs.txt file is, the more
              memory it takes up.  The amount of memory that the DSE-Msgs
              file takes up is the same as the AmigaDOS filesize.

   Again, you may compress any of the files in the Text directory with a
   PowerPacker compatible utility, provided you've copied the included
   powerpacker.library to your LIBS: directory.


9) That's it.  You've installed DSE on your system.  For those of you who
   are wondering where DSEed and DSEmaint are (from older versions of DSE),
   here's what happened:  First of all, DSEmaint is obsolete.  Maintenance
   is built into the game.  So no more nightly cron garbage.  Second, the
   editor is built into DSE, now.  To use it, from the main DSE menu, hit Z
   and then type in the password (the default is "znarf", which IS case
   sensitive).  To change the password, load up the DSE-Msgs.txt file and
   change line number 774.  Use the editor at your own risk.  If you don't
   know what you're doing, you can screw things up.


                                    -@{"David Prothero" link AUTHR}

@ENDNODE

@NODE CODES "Text File Codes"

   Each code starts with a CONTROL-Y character.  Make sure your text editor
   can handle this.  If you save a menu file in a text editor that does not
   display the CONTROL-Y character, then all the codes will be RUINED.  I
   know that CygnusEd works fine.

   After the CONTROL-Y comes the one character code and then a one
   character parameter.  Some codes don't take parameters, so any
   character will work here.

   Available codes:

   Code    Parameter(s)   Description

   c       0-9 and a-f    Changes foreground color of all subsequent text.

                          0 - Black      1 - Red        2 - Green   
                          3 - Orange     4 - Blue       5 - Purple
                          6 - Cyan       7 - Lt. Grey   8 - Dk. Grey
                          9 - Lt. Red    a - Lt. Green  b - Yellow
                          c - Lt. Blue   d - Lt. Purple e - Lt. Cyan
                          f - White

                          Colors are remapped when running from a Shell.


   z       0-7            Changes background color of all subsequent text.
                          Colors are the same as above, except, only the
                          first eight may be used (ANSI restriction).
                          Background colors are not seen from Shell mode.


   n       1-9            Adds a "newline", which is a carriage return and
                          a linefeed.  The parameter is the number of
                          newlines to add.


   g       0              Pauses for user to hit a key.  Just supply 0 as
                          the parameter.


   f       0-1            Supplying  the 0 parameter will just move the cursor
                          back to "home" position (upper-left).  Supplying
                          the 1 parameter will clear the screen completely.

   q       1              Resets current color to "f" (white) and the
                          background color to "0" (black).  Just supply 1
                          as the parameter.


   For example, the text: c9Hello, n2what is your name?g1f1

   Would display the following in Light Red:

   Hello,

   What is your name?<wait for a keypress><clear screen>


   Anyway, CNet SysOps will recognize these codes.  I'm using them because
   this program was originally a CNet door and used those codes.  Instead
   of re-writing all the text, I did it this way, which seemed more
   flexible, anyway.  Sorry to Excelsior! users who'll have to learn this
   different code, but just remember to use a CONTROL-Y instead of a \
   character.

@ENDNODE

